### ✅ What is **Prototype** in JavaScript?

In JavaScript, **prototype** is the mechanism by which **objects inherit properties and methods from other objects**.

***

## 🔹 Simple Definition (Interview‑ready)

> A **prototype** is an object from which other objects inherit properties and methods in JavaScript.

***

## 🔹 Key Idea to Remember

✅ JavaScript uses **prototype‑based inheritance**  
✅ Every object has an internal link to another object called its **prototype**  
✅ This link forms a **prototype chain**

***

## 🔹 Two Important Terms (Very Important 🔥)

### 1️⃣ `__proto__` (internal / instance side)

*   Exists on **every JavaScript object**
*   Points to the object’s prototype

### 2️⃣ `prototype` (constructor side)

*   Exists **only on constructor functions**
*   Used as a blueprint for objects created with `new`

***

## ✅ Basic Example

```js
const obj = {};
```

Prototype chain:

    obj → Object.prototype → null

```js
obj.toString(); // works
```

✅ `toString()` comes from `Object.prototype`

***

## ✅ Constructor Function Example

```js
function Person(name) {
  this.name = name;
}

Person.prototype.greet = function () {
  console.log("Hello " + this.name);
};

const p1 = new Person("Raja");
```

### 🔹 Prototype Chain

    p1
     ↓ __proto__
    Person.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓
    null

✅ `p1.greet()` works because of prototype lookup

***

## 🔍 How Property Lookup Works (Very Important)

When you access a property:

```js
p1.greet();
```

JavaScript looks in this order:

1.  `p1` object
2.  `Person.prototype`
3.  `Object.prototype`
4.  `null` → stop

✅ First match wins

***

## ✅ `prototype` vs `__proto__` (Classic Interview Question)

```js
p1.__proto__ === Person.prototype; // ✅ true
```

| Term        | Belongs To  | Purpose                 |
| ----------- | ----------- | ----------------------- |
| `prototype` | Constructor | Blueprint for instances |
| `__proto__` | Object      | Points to its prototype |

***

## ✅ ES6 Classes (Same Under the Hood)

```js
class Person {
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
}

const p = new Person();
```

Prototype chain:

    p → Person.prototype → Object.prototype → null

📌 **Classes are just syntactic sugar over prototypes**

***

## ✅ Inheritance Using Prototype (`extends`)

```js
class Employee extends Person {
  work() {
    console.log("Working");
  }
}

const e = new Employee();
```

Prototype chain:

    e
     ↓
    Employee.prototype
     ↓
    Person.prototype
     ↓
    Object.prototype
     ↓
    null

✅ This is how JavaScript achieves inheritance

***

## ✅ Object.create() (Direct Prototype Control)

```js
const parent = {
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
};

const child = Object.create(parent);
```

Prototype chain:

    child → parent → Object.prototype → null

✅ No constructor needed  
✅ Very clean prototype inheritance

***

## 🔥 Why Prototype Is Important

✅ Memory efficiency (methods shared)  
✅ Inheritance  
✅ Method reuse  
✅ Foundation of `class` and `extends`  
✅ Understanding bugs & performance

***

## ✅ Common Interview Traps

### ❓ Is prototype copying?

❌ No — it's **referencing**, not copying

***

### ❓ Do all objects have a prototype?

✅ Yes (except objects created with `Object.create(null)`)

***

### ❓ Is prototype the same as class?

❌ No — **classes use prototypes internally**

***

## ✅ One‑Line Interview Answer

> Prototype is the mechanism by which JavaScript objects inherit properties and methods from other objects through a prototype chain.

***

## ✅ 10‑Second Interview Explanation

> Every JavaScript object has a prototype, and when a property is not found on the object, JavaScript looks up the prototype chain until it finds the property or reaches null.

***

## ✅ Real‑World Tip (React / JS)

*   Many bugs happen due to **prototype shadowing**
*   Understanding prototypes helps debug `undefined is not a function`
*   Libraries & frameworks rely heavily on prototypes

